## Building a Pagination Component in Angular

**Mental model:** Pagination is controlled — `page` in, `pageChange` out (the `xxxChange` name enables `[(page)]`). The component renders prev/next plus page buttons; the only real logic is *which numbers to show* — first, last, current ±siblings, with ellipses for gaps. A getter derives that range. Classic `NgModule` setup, no `?.`/`??` (the build rejects them).

### Step 1 — Input/output control
```typescript
@Input() page = 1;
@Input() total = 1;
@Input() siblings = 1;
@Output() pageChange = new EventEmitter<number>();
go(p: number): void { this.pageChange.emit(p); }
```

### Step 2 — Derive the range with a getter
```typescript
get range(): (number | string)[] {
  const r: (number | string)[] = [];
  for (let p = 1; p <= this.total; p++) {
    if (p === 1 || p === this.total || Math.abs(p - this.page) <= this.siblings) { r.push(p); }
    else if (r[r.length - 1] !== '…') { r.push('…'); }
  }
  return r;
}
```

### Step 3 — Render numbers vs ellipsis
Use `*ngIf`/`else` to split the dots from clickable numbers.

```html
<ng-container *ngFor="let p of range">
  <span *ngIf="p === '…'; else num">…</span>
  <ng-template #num><button (click)="go(asNumber(p))">{{ p }}</button></ng-template>
</ng-container>
```

### Step 4 — Prev / Next with bounds
```html
<button [disabled]="page === 1" (click)="go(page - 1)">‹</button>
<button [disabled]="page === total" (click)="go(page + 1)">›</button>
```

**Edge cases**

| Case | Handling |
| :-- | :-- |
| Few pages | Range is contiguous, no ellipsis. |
| Current at edge | First/last always kept; no duplicates. |
| total = 1 | `*ngIf="total > 1"` hides the control. |

**Interview tip:** Because the template can't narrow the `number | string` union, a tiny `asNumber()` helper keeps the click handler typed — calling that out shows you're thinking about Angular's strict template type-checking.

